Introduction to Priority Queues using Binary Heaps

What is Priority Queue ?
A Priority Queue is a special type of queue where each element is assigned a priority, and instead of being processed in the order they arrive (like a normal queue), the element with
the highest priority is always processed first.

explained with example of hospital patients

Binary Heap:
A Binary Heap is a Binary Tree that satisfies the following conditions.

It should be a Complete Binary Tree.
It should satisfy the Heap property.

Complete Binary Tree:
The tree in Which all the levels are completely filled except the last level and last level is filled in such a way that all the keys are as left as possible.


Heap Property:
Binary Heap is either a Min Heap or Max Heap. Property of the Binary Heap decides whether it is Min Heap or Max Heap.

Min Heap property: For every node in a binary heap, if the node value is less than its right and left child’s value then Binary Heap is known as Min Heap.
Max Heap property: For every node in a binary heap, if the node value is greater than its right and left child’s value then Binary Heap is known as Max Heap.

Representation of the Binary Heap
A Binary Heap is represented as an array.

The root value is at arr[0]
The below table summarizes how the node and its children are stored in an array.

Node index: i
Left child Index: 2*i+1
Right Child Index: 2*i+2


If the child is at index i, then its parent index can be found using the below formula.
Child’s Index: i
Parent’s Index: (i-1)/2



Operations Associated with Min Heap
Insert() 
Heapify()
getMin()
ExtractMin()
Delete()
Decreasekey()


Min Heap and Max Heap Implementation

PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>();
PriorityQueue<Integer> maxHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());

Convert min Heap to max Heap and vice versa

🔁 1️⃣ If you are using Java PriorityQueue (most practical)

✅ Min Heap → Max Heap
PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>();

PriorityQueue<Integer> maxHeap =
        new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());

maxHeap.addAll(minHeap);

✅ Max Heap → Min Heap
PriorityQueue<Integer> maxHeap =
        new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());

PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>();

minHeap.addAll(maxHeap);


📌 Time Complexity:
O(n) average (heapify during bulk insertion)


🔹 Min Heap → Max Heap
public static void minToMaxHeap(int[] arr) {
    int n = arr.length;

    for (int i = n / 2 - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        maxHeapify(arr, n, i);
    }
}

private static void maxHeapify(int[] arr, int n, int i) {
    int largest = i;
    int left = 2 * i + 1;
    int right = 2 * i + 2;

    if (left < n && arr[left] > arr[largest])
        largest = left;

    if (right < n && arr[right] > arr[largest])
        largest = right;

    if (largest != i) {
        int temp = arr[i];
        arr[i] = arr[largest];
        arr[largest] = temp;

        maxHeapify(arr, n, largest);
    }
}

🧠 Interview One-liner Answer

To convert Min Heap to Max Heap, rebuild the heap by applying max-heapify from the last non-leaf node. This takes O(n) time.